I'm using GamePadState constructor that takes an array of Buttons:

``` csharp
public GamePadState(Vector2 leftThumbStick, Vector2 rightThumbStick, float leftTrigger, float rightTrigger, params Buttons[] buttons)
```

And later checking state.DPad.\* to see if buttons are pressed or not. However, the above mentioned constructor appears to ignore the passed list of buttons when constructing GamePadDPad.

Here is a test which passes against XNA but fails against MonoGame that illustrates the problem:

``` csharp
        [Test]
        [TestCase((Buttons)0, new[] { ButtonState.Released, ButtonState.Released, ButtonState.Released, ButtonState.Released })]
        [TestCase(Buttons.DPadDown, new[] { ButtonState.Pressed, ButtonState.Released, ButtonState.Released, ButtonState.Released })]
        [TestCase(Buttons.DPadLeft, new[] { ButtonState.Released, ButtonState.Pressed, ButtonState.Released, ButtonState.Released })]
        [TestCase(Buttons.DPadRight, new[] { ButtonState.Released, ButtonState.Released, ButtonState.Pressed, ButtonState.Released })]
        [TestCase(Buttons.DPadUp, new[] { ButtonState.Released, ButtonState.Released, ButtonState.Released, ButtonState.Pressed })]
        public void ConstructorWithButtonsArrayConstructsInternalDPadStateCorrectly(Buttons button, ButtonState[] expectedDPadButtonStates)
        {
            var state = new GamePadState(Vector2.Zero, Vector2.Zero, 0f, 0f, button != 0 ? new Buttons[] { button } : new Buttons[] {});

            if(button != 0)
                Assert.True(state.IsButtonDown(button));
            Assert.AreEqual(expectedDPadButtonStates[0], state.DPad.Down, "DPad.Down Pressed or Released");
            Assert.AreEqual(expectedDPadButtonStates[1], state.DPad.Left, "DPad.Left Pressed or Released");
            Assert.AreEqual(expectedDPadButtonStates[2], state.DPad.Right, "DPad.Right Pressed or Released");
            Assert.AreEqual(expectedDPadButtonStates[3], state.DPad.Up, "DPad.Up Pressed or Released");
        }
```

Please note that this is similar to, but different than, Issue #1055.

Effects on a model processed with the SkinnedModel pipeline example are set to BasicEffect when they should be set to SkinnedEffect

The skinned content processor has this code 

```
        /// <summary>
        /// Force all the materials to use our skinned model effect.
        /// </summary>
        [DefaultValue(MaterialProcessorDefaultEffect.SkinnedEffect)]
        public override MaterialProcessorDefaultEffect DefaultEffect
        {
            get { return MaterialProcessorDefaultEffect.SkinnedEffect; }
            set { }
        }
```

However this appears to have no effect on the XNB output. In fact I can't find any references to the `MaterialProcessorDefaultEffect` in the MonoGame codebase.

Any ideas where this is normally used to set the correct material?
